-Creepy <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#6B8E23><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub10.ezboard.com/ukrystl.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Krystl</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_star.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#5F9EA0>(11/27/01 1:40:25 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub10.ezboard.com/fforgottentruthforeignlegiongeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=755.topic&index=11>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Midgard</span><hr size=1> When I originally asked the guild to move the server for Midgard to Test instead of Guinevere, it was very sefishly done.  I often lag so badly in Palomides on Friday and Saturday nights that the game is almost not playable, however, I could go to Test and do just fine.  Also, the dungeons are so crowded, that people become hostile, and the playing atmosphere is often of a lesser quality during peak times. <br>
<br>
The concerns regarding R vs R are very valid, and I agree that there are just not the numbers to do so on Test in any normal way.  However, we have yet to accomplish much in R vs R on Palomides, so I suppose I was not thinking we'd be ready for that on a 2nd server so soon.  I was picturing playing on Midgard as more recreational until we had matured into high-level characters on the first server.  I was envisioning a revolving process where we played one realm and accomplished great feats as a guild and as individuals, then moved on to the next realm until we had conquered all 3.  I am guilty of liking to play lowbies of new races in different terrain as much as the next person, but I have a fear of the guild becoming too split and seperated.  I had tried to make Friday night Test night, to give everyone an opportunity to still play together, but get variety, but that was met with lukewarm acceptance, only a handful of people joined me.<br>
<br>
My question to the guild is:  To what extent do we want to play on another server in another realm?  Do we just want a haven to play in when boredom strikes, or are we already moving on before we make our mark in our current world?  We have done GREAT as a guild, and I am so happy with how we play together, share, treat everyone with respect, and even though we have grown in numbers every week, I still feel a great sense of family among us, and that is exactly how I think it should be.  I would enjoy having a level 50 character in each realm eventually, and experience as much of each that there is to offer, but only if I have my guildmates with me to enjoy the experience.  I feel that we work well together, and that we could make great contributions to our land.  Our potential is great - perhaps much greater than alot of guilds that are built on recruiting #s instead of people...  I like to think of each of us as an individual, and I miss those of you that do not play often on Palomides, and always look forward to seeing each and every one of you any chance I get.  I think most of us feel this way! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
That being said, I DO think we should decide upon a server for each realm, and create a guild there as soon as possible too, for ease in finding our friends there.  Don't misunderstand.  I will probably spend time in each on occassion even now, but I would like to stick to one main, so that we might remain together and experience the new things together as a family - as our guild.  <br>
<br>
My vote will be to stick with the guild's original decision to play on Guinevere for Midgard. <p>Krystl</i>, Albion Cleric of Palomides<br>
